article.description: Ruth Riley scored 18 points, including the game-winning basket with 1 second left, to lead the Shock to a 60-59 victory at San Antonio on Saturday night.
article.headline: Detroit a half-game out of final East playoff spot
article.linkText: Riley's putback with :01 left gives Shock 4th win in row
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Ruth Riley scored 20 points, including the
game-winning basket with 1 second left, to lead the Detroit Shock
over the San Antonio Silver Stars 60-59 Saturday night.

Shannon Johnson's turnaround jumper for San Antonio near the
3-point line bounced off the back of the rim as the buzzer sounded,
giving the Shock (14-14) their fourth straight win.

Detroit is one-half game behind Washington for the fourth and
final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. It's the first time
the Shock have been at .500 since they were 7-7 on July 7.

"I think that we will need to finish at least 4-2 to be assured
of a playoff spot," Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said.

The Silver Stars took a 59-58 lead when Marie Ferdinand hit a
3-pointer with 7 seconds left. Ferdinand scored a game-high 21
points, but the Silver Stars (7-23) lost their fifth straight game
for the third time this season.

Riley's game-winner came when she rebounded Katie Smith's missed
shot on a drive into the lane with 3 seconds left.

"Once Katie's shot went up, it was just a matter of being in
the right place at the right time," said Riley, who topped her
previous season-high of 11 points. "I've had great looks all
season. But I haven't had the consistency that I would like.
Tonight I just felt good and the shots started falling."

The Shock lead the league in rebounding, but were outworked
39-33 by San Antonio. Cheryl Ford, leading the WNBA with 10.0
rebounds per game, was limited to three.

Trailing by 12 with just less than 7 minutes left in the first
half, Detroit cut the deficit to 29-26 by halftime. The Shock tied
the game for the first time on Smith's 3-pointer with 16 minutes
left in the game.

Detroit is 5-2 since obtaining Smith in a trade July 31 from
Minnesota, and has won three straight since with her in the
starting lineup.

Ferdinand didn't score until 5:19 into the game. But as soon as
she did, the Silver Stars went on a 19-8 run over the next 6:58
that turned a 5-4 lead into a 24-12 advantage. Ferdinand was
outscoring Detroit 13-12 at that time.

"We played our best game," Ferdinand said. "We gave Detroit
everything we had. It's tough to swallow."
